# UI And UX Guidelines

- Keep layouts stable. Avoid inserting or removing content above an already-rendered primary result, especially graph canvases, tables, image regions, forms, and validation blocks.
- Prefer non-displacing feedback for secondary state changes: overlay a compact note inside the existing result frame, update a stable header/control label, use an inline badge, or place status text in an existing side/detail panel. Reserve blank vertical space only when the reserved area is intentionally part of the composition and closely matches the expected content height.
- Show clear async states for data fetching, imports, mutations, and graph traversal. Disable or busy-mark controls when duplicate actions would be harmful.
- Avoid loading flicker. Use a short minimum display duration only for visible skeletons or spinners when it improves perceived stability; do not artificially delay fast content updates.
- Pair loading states with useful empty and error states. Empty states should explain what happened and offer a next action; errors should be recoverable when possible.
- Ensure layouts work across screen sizes. Design mobile, tablet, and desktop behavior intentionally, especially for graph visualizations, side panels, forms, and long text.
- Preserve keyboard and screen-reader usability. Interactive states should have visible `focus-visible` styles for keyboard focus only, meaningful labels, semantic elements, and ARIA only where native semantics are insufficient.
- Make clickable elements visibly interactive. Use `cursor: pointer` and provide clear hover and focus states for buttons, links, selectable graph nodes, and custom controls so users can discover what can be clicked.
- Use `Link.vue` for text that navigates to another route or external URL, so users learn one consistent treatment for clickable navigational text.
- Do not use `Link.vue` for every navigational surface. Header nav items, brand marks, CTA buttons, and route-card surfaces may keep contextual `RouterLink` or `<a>` styling when their shape, label, hover state, and focus state already make the navigation affordance clear.
- Avoid one-off hover, underline, focus, or color classes on ordinary text links. If the link is just text, use the shared `Link.vue` treatment.
- When a popover or menu is open, its trigger should use the shared `active` button state so the open control remains visibly connected to the floating surface.
- Follow established interaction conventions. Buttons, links, forms, menus, comboboxes, focus behavior, keyboard shortcuts, scrolling, and browser affordances should behave the way users expect unless there is a clear product reason to diverge.
- Do not make custom UI clever at the expense of predictability. Prefer native platform behavior and familiar patterns over surprising gestures, hidden interactions, or non-standard control semantics.
- Keep motion purposeful and modest. Use animation to clarify transitions or graph changes, and respect reduced-motion preferences for non-essential movement.
- Prefer progressive disclosure for dense etymology data. Show the most important relationship first, then reveal metadata, source details, and raw text on demand.
- Show languages by canonical name in user-facing UI. Do not display language codes such as `en`, `pgd`, or `ine-pro` unless the canonical name is unavailable and the code is the only fallback.

## Loading Skeletons

- Use `Skeleton.vue` when a primary content frame has a predictable shape and loading would otherwise leave a large blank area, such as result lists, entry detail panels, graph side panels, and stable search result regions.
- Prefer skeletons that preserve the final layout height and hierarchy. Match expected headings, rows, blocks, or graph reference slips closely enough to prevent layout shift without faking exact content.
- For loading lists, render item-shaped skeletons that match the final row, chip, card, or menu-item rhythm instead of plain loading copy such as "Finding nearby entries". Keep skeleton items in the same row/wrap behavior as the loaded content, and size them to the equivalent control footprint, such as the same height and approximate width as the buttons they replace.
- Do not use skeletons for quick control-level feedback, background refetches, or secondary state changes inside an already-rendered result. Use button loading states, `aria-busy`, an inline label, or `StatusNote.vue` instead.
- Keep skeletons decorative and quiet: use semantic theme tokens, modest opacity pulse, `prefers-reduced-motion`, sharp paper-like corners, and no bright shimmer sweeps or glossy gradients.
- Pair skeleton regions with accessible loading state on the parent container, such as `aria-busy="true"` or a visually available loading label when the state is not otherwise announced.
- Avoid loading flicker. Render skeletons only when a loading state is likely to be visible long enough to help orientation; do not delay fast successful content solely to show them.

## Empty States

- Empty states should explain what happened without implying the user's query is wrong. For incomplete local data, prefer copy like "No imported matches" over absolute claims like "No relationships exist."
- Avoid raised surfaces, shadows, and result-card styling for empty states unless the empty state itself contains a primary interactive workflow. Raised treatment can make a non-result look clickable or expandable.
- Include a recovery path whenever possible: preset searches, a reset action, a related filter change, or guidance on which control to adjust next.
- Keep empty states quieter than successful results. Use page text, light dividers, subtle borders, or inline notes before adding large cards.
- When offering recovery presets, filter them against available data so the empty state does not suggest impossible or unavailable choices.

## Available UI Components

- Prefer shared primitives from `apps/web/src/uiComponents/` before styling one-off low-level controls.
- `Badge.vue`: use for compact, passive metadata labels such as statuses, relationship types, required markers, and non-interactive categories. Use `variant="custom"` with a caller-provided `--badge-color` when a badge should inherit a local semantic color.
- `Button.vue`: use for compact, text-labeled actions, form submits, destructive actions, loading states, full-width actions, and active popover/menu triggers. Buttons work best for short single-line labels; when a choice needs explanatory copy, metadata, or multiple lines of text, prefer a purpose-built interactive row, slip, or card with native button/link semantics so the larger content does not feel like a button stuffed with prose.
- `IconButton.vue`: use for compact icon-only actions. Always pass a clear `label`; use `active` when it controls an open or selected state.
- `Link.vue`: use for prose, metadata, breadcrumb, and other text links that navigate to routes or external URLs. Use `variant="plain"` only when wrapping a child that already has clear link affordance, such as a linked badge.
- `TextField.vue`: use for labeled text-like inputs with help text, required copy, validation copy, and `v-model`.
- `TextFieldBase.vue`: use only inside higher-level input components when the label, help text, and validation wrapper are supplied elsewhere.
- `Combobox.vue`: use when users type to filter or choose from a known option list, including search/select flows with empty states and optional custom values.
- `Select.vue`: use for small to medium curated option sets where scanability is better than text filtering. Prefer it over `Combobox.vue` when the selected value should not become a search query.
- `Popover.vue`: use for anchored non-modal floating content such as filters, metadata panels, small forms, and disclosure surfaces.
- `Skeleton.vue`: use for decorative placeholders that preserve stable loading layouts. Set accessible loading semantics on the parent region rather than on each skeleton piece.
- `StatusNote.vue`: use for compact contextual status messages, especially non-displacing overlays inside graph/data result frames. Make persistent explanatory notes dismissible when they may obscure content.
- `ContextMenu.vue`: use for action menus tied to a trigger or contextual graph/item target; keep options short, predictable, and keyboard accessible.
- `MenuItem.vue`: use inside menu-like listbox surfaces to keep option, selected, highlighted, and disabled styling consistent.
- `Divider.vue`: use for semantic horizontal separation between page sections, grouped controls, menus, and compact panels. Do not use ad hoc `border-b`, `border-t`, or one-off `<hr>` styling when a standalone section divider is the thing being rendered.
- This directory is intentionally not a complete design system. If an agent thinks a new low-level reusable component is needed, it should confirm with Will before building so he can weigh in on whether it is needed and how it should work.
